Linear Regression¶

In [19]:
counts = imputed.count()
print("EM Thickness Readings are easier to take than measurements from an Auger.")
print("This dataset contains", counts["Ice Thickness"], "manual readings, and", counts["EM Thick"], "EM readings.")
print("Thus, we want to examine how much we can trust those measurements by exploring the relationship between them.\n")

# Plot the relationship between Ice Thickness and EM Thickness
lr = sns.lmplot(data=bigset, x="Ice Thickness", y="EM Thick")
rsd = sns.residplot(data=bigset, x="Ice Thickness", y="EM Thick")

# Calculate model fit
slope, intercept, r_value, p_value, _ = stats.linregress(bigset['Ice Thickness'].values,bigset['EM Thick'].values)
equation = "y = " + '{0:.2f}'.format(slope) + "x + " + '{0:.2f}'.format(intercept)
num_samples = len(bigset['Ice Thickness'].values)
num_inpdt_var = 1
adj_r2 = 1-(1-(r_value**2)*(num_samples-1)/(num_samples-num_inpdt_var-1))
print(equation)
print("Adjusted R^2 Value:", adj_r2)
print("P Value:", p_value)
print("The adjusted R^2 Value and low P value demonstrate there is a high correlation between these variables, and our model captures a significant portion of the variance.")

def em_to_ice_thick(x):
    return slope * x + intercept

EM Thickness Readings are easier to take than measurements from an Auger.
This dataset contains 469 manual readings, and 21539 EM readings.
Thus, we want to examine how much we can trust those measurements by exploring the relationship between them.

P Value: 2.313840006273919e-202

Imputing Model Values¶

In [20]:
# Imputing
imputed['isTruth'] = imputed['Ice Thickness'].apply(lambda x: False if math.isnan(float(x)) else True)

for index, row in imputed.iterrows():
    if not row.isTruth:
        data = row['EM Thick']
        res = em_to_ice_thick(data)
        imputed.at[index, 'Ice Thickness'] = res

imputed['deltaThick'] = imputed['EM Thick'] - imputed['EM Thick'].shift(-1)
dfg = imputed.groupby(by=["Latitude", "Longitude"])
track1 = dfg.get_group((84.667, 5.1))

# Plotting the simulated sea ice thickness
fig, axes = plt.subplots(4, 1, figsize=(10, 10))
plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.8)
ax1 = sns.lineplot(data=track1, x="Position", y="Ice Thickness", hue="isTruth", ax=axes[0]).set_title('Ice Thickness (projected)')
ax2 = sns.lineplot(data=track1, x="Position", y="deltaThick", hue="isTruth", ax=axes[1]).set_title('EM Thickness Changes (known)')
ax3 = sns.histplot(data=track1, x="deltaThick", ax=axes[2], kde=True).set_title('Ice Thickness Distribution')

norm_data = normalize([track1.deltaThick], norm="max").flatten()
st_dev = np.std(norm_data)

ax4 = sns.histplot(data=norm_data, ax=axes[3], kde=True).set_title('Ice Thickness Distribution (Normalized)')
plt.vlines(x=[st_dev * -3, st_dev  *-2, st_dev * -1, st_dev, st_dev * 2, st_dev * 3], ymin=0, ymax=110, color='red', linestyles='dashed')
print("Normalized Standard Deviation: ", st_dev)
k2, p = stats.normaltest(track1.deltaThick)
alpha = 1e-3
sm.qqplot(track1.deltaThick, line='45')

print("Normalized Test p-value = {:g}".format(p))
if p < alpha:  # null hypothesis: x comes from a normal distribution
    print("The null hypothesis can be rejected")
else:
    print("The null hypothesis cannot be rejected")
plt.show()

Final Remarks / Conclusion¶

A few conclusions can be made from this exploratory data analysis:

  • There is a strong relationship between manual measurements of ice thickness and EM measurements of ice thickness.
    • This relationship falls off as ice thickness increases, but that is a limitation of this data source
  • Not every track follows a normal distribution, but longer length tracks tend to look like they do.
    • This makes some sense, as some sections of ice may have irregularly jagged or smooth underwater surfaces leading to a skewed distribution. As the set captures more data it makes sense that the distribution looks more normal.
    • It's apparent through the normalized test and Q-Q Chart that even the longest track that looks normally distributed, isn't.
    • The Q-Q chart suggests that the data set includes too much data in the extremities.
    • As it stands, further statistical analysis will need to follow non-parametric methods because of the non-normal distribution. It may be possible to adjust the data / scale to make the data more normal though.
    • More investigation needs to be done to find whether these relationships hold for temporally and spatially different ice regions.

It's important to notice that this exact analysis concerns the physical ice thickness. From the charts above, it's possible to visualize the cross-section of the ice sheet by plotting along-track ice depth but the axis will need to be inverted to represent depth going in the downwards direction. It's also important to notice that the distributions plotted were of the change in ice thickness per unit of measurement, not of direct ice thickness.

Ideally, the general relationships of ice thickness will be applied to other remote sensing methods (such as ICESat-2's ATLAS) to get a better understanding of what the sea ice could look like. If further investigation were to prove a similar distribution of ice thickness (in spatially and temporally different regions), it would be reasonable to preprocess data from ICESat-2 to more closely resemble that pattern.

At the moment, I'm concerned with modeling the freeboard height measurements of ice by correlating SAR imaging with ICESat-2's laser altimeter. Until the European Space Agency (ESA) approves of my project proposal and allows access to ICEYE's high-resolution SPOT imaging, research will need to be done to prepare other data sources for correlation. Though this specific analysis concerns sea ice thickness and not freeboard depth, I hope the insight becomes more valuable as the project continues.
